article.description: Baron Davis scored 20 points off the bench in his first game in over a month to lead the surging Hornets to an 81-71 victory over the reeling Pacers, who have dropped five straight games.
article.headline: Davis: 20 points in 24 minutes after six weeks away
article.linkText: Hornets' Davis scores 20 after six weeks away
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indiana's season continues to unravel quicker than Ron Artest's temper.
Davis

Baron Davis scored 20 points in his first game in six weeks as the New Orleans Hornets beat Indiana 81-71 Tuesday night for the Pacers' fifth straight loss and 11th in 12 games. The Pacers' locker room was closed for nearly 40 minutes for a team meeting to address concerns about selfishness that have crept into what was a close-knit team. "Right now, everyone is very self-absorbed in terms of himself, his play, and his performance,'' coach Isiah Thomas said. "When you become very self-absorbed, you don't think about team.'' The Pacers were playing their first game at home following a disastrous 0-4 West Coast trip. Their problems followed them home, where they were booed by their fans. The Pacers -- specifically Artest and Al Harrington -- appeared to have abandoned Thomas' "Quick" offense, a read-and-react system that stresses movement and equal opportunity. There was little passing on Tuesday, as Harrington or Artest would get the ball and either fire up a poor shot or wait until the shot clock ticked down to drive the lane and run into a double team. "The ball is stopping. It's not moving anywhere,'' Thomas said. "Even when we make a pass on the perimeter, there's a stop and a hold. Wait and see. There's no trust to give the ball up and get it back and play together.'' Artest didn't start, sat out the third quarter and shot 2-for-7 for eight points. Harrington made eight of 20 shots for 21 points and Jermaine O'Neal scored 19, also on 8-for-20 shooting. "I think some of what's happened is that over time, guys got confident in our offense and got away from what made us successful early,'' Harrington said. While the Pacers -- and New Jersey and Detroit -- have slumped for the past month, the Hornets have rapidly gained ground. The Hornets avoided a four-game season sweep by Indiana and gained a game on the Pacers in the Central Division. The Hornets have lost only once since Feb. 18, pushing them into contention for first place in the Eastern Conference. Davis came off the injured list Monday after missing 20 games with torn cartilage in his left knee. Davis was hurt Jan. 26, and his six-week rehabilitation gave him a chance to also rest and treat a herniated disk that was a problem earlier in the season. "My first three or four minutes, I was a little anxious, a little out of control,'' Davis said. "As I started to settle down and get into a nice flow, it seems like things started working for me.'' Davis did not start, but didn't appear very rusty, making a few nice drives to the basket and finishing 9-for-14 from the floor. I didn't think I was going to score 20 points, but I did and we needed it and we won,'' he said. The Pacers used an 8-0 run to lead 67-66, but Kenny Anderson put the Hornets ahead for good with a couple of baskets and Davis clinched it with a 3-pointer over the 7-foot Jonathan Bender. Jamaal Magloire had 10 points and 12 rebounds, David Wesley had 14 points and P.J. Brown had 10 rebounds for New Orleans. The Pacers lost center Brad Miller early in the third quarter when he reaggravated his sore left foot. The injury caused Miller to miss Indiana's game on Sunday. The Pacers also were without starting guard Jamaal Tinsley, who left the team to be with his ailing mother. Without Miller, the Pacers turned a 42-36 halftime deficit into a 46-42 lead before Wesley hit a 3-pointer and Davis had two baskets in the final minute to end the third tied at 59. The schedule doesn't get easier for the Pacers, who play another surging team -- Philadelphia -- on Wednesday. "We know what we've got to work our way back to,'' Thomas said. "That's not going to come from shooting 25 shots or working on your 3-point game, working on your post moves and all that. You've got to get back to being a good team and trusting and respecting your teammates.''

Game notes
Thomas didn't know when Tinsley would return. He missed one game last month for the same reason. ... A pregnant fan wore a half-shirt, exposing a yellow basketball painted on her belly. ... The Pacers placed G Fred Jones on the injured list. ... Wesley hurt his back and ribs in the second quarter when he collided with Artest going for a loose ball. ... Thomas and Bender were whistled for technicals.
